  "prompt": "Why does Apple not put a Flashlight on the iPad?",
  "response": "Apple has not included a dedicated flashlight feature on the iPad for several reasons, primarily related to the design, intended use case, and hardware limitations of the device:\n\n1. **Lack of a Flash LED**: iPads do not have a built-in LED flash on the rear camera, unlike iPhones. This hardware limitation makes it impossible to use the camera flash as a flashlight.\n\n2. **Primary Use Case**: iPads are designed as larger, productivity-focused devices rather than compact, on-the-go tools like iPhones. The need for a flashlight is less critical for a device typically used indoors or for tasks like browsing, content creation, and media consumption.\n\n3. **Screen as an Alternative**: The iPad's large display can serve as a makeshift light source when needed. By increasing the screen brightness to maximum or displaying a white screen, users can achieve a similar effect to a dedicated flashlight.\n\n4. **Battery Considerations**: Actively using the screen or a hypothetical LED flash as a flashlight would drain the battery more quickly, which could be counterproductive for a device designed for longer usage sessions.\n\n5. **Simplified Feature Set**: Apple often avoids adding features that may not align with the device's core functionality, keeping the user experience focused and streamlined.\n\nWhile a dedicated flashlight app isn\u2019t available, users can rely on third-party apps or the screen itself for light-related needs. If a flashlight feature is essential, pairing an iPhone with the iPad or using an external light source is a practical solution.",
